  Brainrot Lab — Codebase Analysis

  1. Current Architecture

  Style: classic Roblox server-authoritative singleton, organized by game domain.

  - State is centralized in one module (DataManager) — every domain script mutates the same in-memory table keyed by
  UserId. There's no ORM, no events, no per-player objects. Mutations are bare table writes: data.RotPoints += 100.
  - Servers are split by feature, not by player: each game system (Economy, Fusion, Trade, Glitch, Rebirth, Rewards,
  Inventory, Monetization) is a separate Script in its own folder under scripts/Server/. All of them are independently
  listening on Roblox services or RemoteEvents.
  - Networking is event-based, declared up-front in default.project.json (every RemoteEvent and the one RemoteFunction).  Handlers validate input types, look up state, mutate, and FireClient back. There is no replication for non-Remote
  state — the client only learns things when a handler explicitly pushes them.
  - The two "non-Roblox" modules are DataManager (state I/O) and TradeManager (pure state machine, no service
  dependencies) — everything else is a thin Roblox-event shim around one of them.
  - Asset/data config is shared via UnitDatabase under ReplicatedStorage.Shared — both server and (eventual) client will  require the same table. This is the only piece of data designed to be cross-tier.
  - Toolchain is Rojo 7.7.0 (via Rokit). Filesystem is the source of truth; default.project.json maps folders into the
  DataModel. No tests, no linter, no CI.

  The shape is conventional and works for a small Roblox project — flat handler files, one shared data module, one pure
  logic module. It's straightforward to follow once you know the convention.

