  3. Potential Problems

  Bugs / correctness risks

  - Data race in GlitchEventHandler.startGlitchLoop: the loop does local data = DataManager.Get(player) per iteration,
  but the data.PlacedUnits it samples can shrink between sample and the click handler's read. If the player unplaces
  units during the 8s window, the index may point at a now-removed entry. The handler doesn't check PlacedUnits[index]
  before awarding the bonus, but the bonus is just RotPoints (not a unit grant), so the current logic is OK — but the
  moment Fragments/units get added as glitch rewards, this becomes a use-after-free.
  - Rebirth is destructive and irreversible: wipes OwnedUnits and PlacedUnits client-side with no confirmation flow, no
  ClaimDaily-style grace, and no pre-rebirth snapshot. A misclick or a malicious client re-firing the event costs the
  player everything. Server doesn't gate rate, doesn't require a confirm Remote, and doesn't even verify the player's
  leaderstats agree with the data wipe.
  - Rebirth does not preserve Fragments or Gamepasses semantics correctly: Gamepasses and Fragments survive (good), but
  DailyStreak and LastDailyClaim also survive — the player keeps their streak through a rebirth, which is presumably
  fine but is a design decision worth confirming. More importantly, the leaderboard value for Rot Points is updated but
  the PlacedUnits/OwnedUnits push to the client is missing — RebirthEvent:FireClient(player, data.Rebirths) fires but no  InventoryUpdated. The client (when it exists) will show stale unit counts.
  - DailyRewardHandler streak is fragile to clock drift: uses os.time() server-side. Roblox's os.time() is fine in
  practice, but the streak only increments if elapsed < 2 days — meaning a player who claims at 23:59:59 on day 1 and
  00:00:01 on day 3 loses 1 day of streak, while a player claiming 12 hours late on day 2 keeps it. Not a bug per se,
  but the comment says "no punishment" while there is a soft one.
  - DailyRewardHandler weekly counter ignores order: WeeklyClaims += 1 runs unconditionally on every successful claim,
  so the comment "every 7 daily claims (not necessarily consecutive days)" is correct — but there's no protection if a
  player already got the chest and tries to claim again before 7 more. They can't, because elapsed < SECONDS_IN_DAY
  returns early — but the order of operations is fragile: a future refactor that changes the cooldown would silently
  change weekly behavior.
  - InventoryHandler.UnplaceUnit only removes the first matching entry (break after first match). If a unit name is
  duplicated in PlacedUnits, only one is removed. That's likely the intent (unplace one copy), but the Remote takes a
  unitName not an index — so the client has no way to target a specific placed instance. When the UI distinguishes
  between placed units by position, this will be a problem.
  - TradeHandler.ConfirmTrade lock-in delay re-validates the wrong table after a PlayerRemoving race: if a player leaves  during the 3s task.delay, trade still references them, and the for unitName, count in
  pairs(trade.offers[playerA.UserId]) loop will index into stale state. The EndTrade cleanup in PlayerRemoving runs
  synchronously on the main thread, but task.delay callbacks run on a separate resume and may see the trade already
  removed — TradeManager.BothConfirmed(trade) will return false (confirmations cleared) and the early return is hit, but  the other player gets no notification that the trade was cancelled. There's no TradeStateChanged "Aborted" push in
  PlayerRemoving cleanup.
