  Architectural / scaling concerns

  - No client yet, but the server has already committed to a "push" model: every mutation FireClients a fresh InventoryUpdated. When the client arrives, this means every change re-sends the full owned + placed tables. With ~20 units and max 10 placed, that's fine. With
  more, it becomes wasteful. No deltas, no replication, no change-tracking.
  - Mutations are unsynchronized: Rebirth wipes OwnedUnits mid-EconomyLoop iteration over PlacedUnits. The PlacedUnits loop sees the just-emptied table, incomeThisTick = 0, no crash. But if a future system holds a reference into PlacedUnits and the rebirth happens, it
  gets a hole. PlacedUnits is an array; table.remove produces nil holes that ipairs skips but for i, v in pairs() would not. Not exploited today, but a footgun.
  - No transaction/batching layer: a player's save is a single DataStore call with the full table. Autosave every 2 minutes is a pcall(SetAsync) with no UpdateAsync retry-on-conflict, so two players in the same studio playing on the same account (or future cloud-shared
  profiles) could clobber. Realistic only at scale, but the fix is small (use UpdateAsync).
  - DataStore is single-keyed and uncached on read: every Load is a GetAsync with no fallback session locking. If the player's SetAsync from a previous session hadn't finished when the new session's GetAsync ran, you'd silently load the old data. The 120s autosave +
  BindToClose flush is the mitigation; the proper mitigation is ProfileService (called out in CONTRIBUTING.md known gaps).
  - Concurrency model is bare task.spawn/task.delay: GlitchEventHandler uses a per-player while player.Parent do loop. If you have hundreds of players, you have hundreds of concurrent infinite loops doing nothing most of the time (each sleeping 3-6 min). Cheap on Roblox,
  but it's a design that doesn't scale to a heartbeat-driven scheduler (which would be one Heartbeat listener iterating all eligible players).
  - No centralized "remotes registry": every handler does ReplicatedStorage.Remotes.<Name>. Adding a new remote means editing both default.project.json and every script that uses it. If two scripts grab the same RemoteEvent and listen to it independently, you've got the
  "duplicate execution" bug CONTRIBUTING.md warns about. There's no compile-time check, no init script that creates remotes at runtime as a safety net.
  - TradeManager is in-memory only, not in Shared: that's correct for security (client must never see the offers table) but also means no audit log, no persistence of in-flight trades across server restarts. If the server crashes mid-trade, players lose their placed
  items on the offer. Currently not catastrophic because no items move until final confirmation, but worth noting.
  - No rate limiting anywhere: BuyUnit, FuseUnits, Rebirth, GlitchClicked are all client-triggerable with no cooldown. A misbehaving client can spam any of them; worst case is log noise, not exploits (because all are server-validated and idempotent-ish), but it's a DoS
  surface.
  - Fragments currency has no sink: data.Fragments is granted (weekly chest) but never spent — no handler reads it. Either the cosmetic store isn't built yet (in which case Fragments is dead currency), or this is pre-plumbing for a future system. No tests/checks catch
  the leak.
  - GamepassHandler.ownsGamepass early-returns false for id == 0: this is the placeholder safety, but the function name implies "does the player own this gamepass?" and the answer is hard-coded false for all current passes. Every test that calls this expecting real
  behavior will fail silently.

  Design/UX concerns worth flagging

  - The Glitch Fragments mechanic, as currently coded, awards RotPoints, not Fragments. The data model has a Fragments field, the README/contributing call it "Glitch Fragments," but the handler writes to RotPoints. Either the reward is misnamed or the mechanic is
  half-built.
  - The Glitch reward is unrelated to the unit it spawned from — clicking a placed Legendary gives the same 50-150 RP as clicking a Common. With no Fragments, no unit-grant, and no rarity scaling, the "Glitch" is just a random ping-pong minigame.
  - No placement validation against a position grid: PlaceUnit only appends to the list with no coordinates. When the UI is built, there's no spatial information to draw. A re-design pass will be needed.
  - Rebirth at 100k RotPoints is reachable in roughly 5-10 minutes with a few placed Legendaries (300/sec × 6 slots = 1800/sec → 100k in ~55s). The "reset" feels less meaningful than intended.
  - UnplaceUnit accepts any unitName and removes the first match, so the client has no way to pick which placed copy to remove. When multiple of the same unit are placed, the UI cannot target a specific slot.

  ---
  Summary: the architecture is conventional, readable, and defensible for a prototype. The two highest-priority concerns are (1) the race conditions around DataManager/gamepass load timing and trade completion, and (2) the Glitch mechanic being misaligned with its own
  data model — these are real bugs the moment a client ships. Everything else is design debt that can wait until post-launch.
